161a36af [scudmarks@discord] history of ℘
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #The symbol ℘ denotes the Weierstrass elliptic function, introduced by Karl
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #Weierstrass in his Berlin lectures during the 1860s (notably around 1863).
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #While Jacobi had developed elliptic functions via the theta functions and the modular sn/cn/dn
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #trio, Weierstrass sought a simpler, doubly-periodic foundation. He defined:
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #\wp(z; ω1, ω2) = 1⁄z² + \sum(m,n)\neq(0,0) \left[1⁄(z+mω1+nω2)² -
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #1⁄(mω1+nω_2)²\right]
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #The stylized "p" (Unicode U+2118, "script capital P") became standard notation through lecture
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #notes published by students—particularly H. A. Schwarz (1867) and L. Kiepert. Weierstrass himself
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #rarely published; the function disseminated via these transcriptions.
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #• Significance:*
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #• Uniformization: It parameterizes all complex elliptic curves via the cubic relation \wp'²
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #= 4\wp³ - g2\wp - g3.
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #• Addition theorem: Its algebraic addition formula is simpler than Jacobi's.
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #• Solitons/Integrability: The differential equation appears in the KdV equation and
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #pendulum motion.
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #It remains central in algebraic geometry, string theory (torus compactifications), and the study of
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #modular forms.
161a37a3 [kimi-k2.5] #
