161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The ℘ symbol (U+2118, Unicode "SCRIPT CAPITAL P") carries one of typography's great
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #mathematical identity crises—simultaneously representing Weierstrass's elliptic function and, by
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #convergent evolution, the power set operation.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Weierstrass Genesis (1850s)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Karl Weierstrass introduced ℘(z) in his theory of elliptic functions around 1856-1860. The
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #symbol is specifically not a standard script P—it's a stylized lowercase German 'p'
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #(p-Function) with a distinctive looped bowl and extended ascender. Weierstrass chose it to
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #distinguish his p-function from Legendre's earlier elliptic function notation.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #• Critical distinction: In proper mathematical typography, ℘ is not the power set
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #symbol. It is the Weierstrass elliptic function*.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The Power Set Collision (1930s-1970s)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The power set 𝒫(S)—the set of all subsets—traditionally used:
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- 𝒫 (U+1D4AB, Mathematical Script Capital P, added Unicode 3.1)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Or simply "P" in fraktur/script contexts
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The collision occurred because:
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #1. Limited typewriter/composer fonts (1950s-70s) often included ℘ (Weierstrass) but not 𝒫
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #(proper script P)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #2. TeX (Knuth, 1978) originally mapped `\wp` to ℘ for Weierstrass, but early users
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #repurposed it for power sets when `\mathcal{P}` rendered inconsistently
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #3. Unicode 1.0 (1991) included U+2118 as "SCRIPT CAPITAL P" (general category: Symbol, not
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Letter), cementing the dual usage
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Unicode Schism
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #• U+2118 ℘* (Weierstrass p):
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Original name: "SCRIPT CAPITAL P" (misnomer—it's lowercase in origin)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Category: Symbol (So)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Font designers render it with the distinctive Weierstrass loop
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #• U+1D4AB 𝒫* (Mathematical Script Capital P):
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Added Unicode 3.1 (2001) specifically for power sets
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Category: Letter, Uppercase (Lu)
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Part of the Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols block
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Detection in Slop Fountain
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Your `slopfountain.ts` handles this ambiguity in the `stringWidth()` functions:
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #// ℘ is handled as double-width in some contexts, single in others
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #// depending on whether it's treated as Symbol or Letter
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The `discordStringWidth()` function likely miscounts ℘ as width 1 when it's actually 2 in most
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #monospace Unicode contexts, or vice versa depending on normalization.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Modern Resolution
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- ISO 80000-2 (2009) specifies 𝒫 (U+1D4AB) for power sets
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- AMS-LaTeX uses `\wp` strictly for Weierstrass, `\mathcal{P}` or `\mathfrak{P}` for power
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #sets
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #- Programming languages: Python, Julia, and Haskell occasionally use ℘ in math libraries
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #for either meaning—context determines semantics
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #The symbol remains a gestalt ambiguity in mathematical computing: typographically the
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #Weierstrass function, semantically overloaded by decades of limited character sets.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #• In slop fountain context*: If you're generating mathematical content, the
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #`texToUnicode()` function should probably map `\wp` → ℘ (Weierstrass) and `\mathcal{P}` → 𝒫 (Power
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #set), though many legacy texts conflate them.
161a9690 [kimi-k2.5] #
